{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480430"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:43:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:43:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"52"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"52","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/52"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.04,0.02,0.03,0.88]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"52"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103447"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"52","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/52"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"52"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85869"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"130"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2312"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11638"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41970"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103447"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-month history of episodic headaches, palpitations, and sweating. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 170/100 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Blood tests show plasma-free metanephrines at 1400 pmol/L (\u0026lt;300). A CT scan of the abdomen is performed and a representative slice shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate definitive treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chemotherapy","Conservative management","Radionuclide therapy","Sunitinib therapy","Surgical resection"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s symptoms, along with the biochemical findings, indicate a functioning pheochromocytoma. The CT scan of the abdomen reveals a 7 cm heterogeneous adrenal mass involving the right adrenal gland, with areas of necrosis and without involvement of adjacent organs/structures. \u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical resection\u003C/strong\u003E is the mainstay of treatment for pheochromocytomas, aiming to remove the tumour and restore normal hormonal balance. This would effectively address the patient\u0027s symptoms and prevent complications associated with excessive catecholamine release from the tumour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPre-operative management of pheochromocytoma involves controlling hypertension and minimising catecholamine release to mitigate perioperative complications. Patients are often started on alpha-blockers (e.g., phenoxybenzamine) to control blood pressure and prevent hypertensive crises, followed by beta-blockers to counteract tachycardia. Adequate hydration and salt intake are essential to maintain intravascular volume. Close monitoring of blood pressure and fluid status is crucial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative management\u003C/strong\u003E, which might involve close observation without immediate intervention, is not suitable for this patient. Phaeochromocytomas can lead to serious complications such as hypertensive crises, stroke, or heart attack due to excessive catecholamine release. Surgery is generally recommended to remove the tumour and prevent these complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically used as the first-line treatment for adrenal masses, especially those suspected to be pheochromocytomas. Chemotherapy may be considered in certain cases where the tumour is unresectable or has metastasised, but it is not the primary treatment in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESunitinib\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is a tyrosine kinase inhibitor used in the treatment of various types of cancer, but it is not the first-line treatment for phaeochromocytomas. Targeted therapies like sunitinib may have a role in advanced or metastatic cases of phaeochromocytoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadionuclide therapy\u003C/strong\u003E with MIBG (meta-iodobenzylguanidine therapy) can be effective for certain cases of unresectable or metastatic phaeochromocytomas. In this scenario, the patient has a localised adrenal mass without involvement of adjacent organs or structures. In such cases, where the tumour is resectable, surgery is typically the first-line treatment to remove the tumour and normalize hormone levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Management of pheochromocytoma involves surgical resection for localized tumours and pre-operative alpha-blockade followed by beta-blockade to stabilize blood pressure and minimize perioperative complications."],"references":["Lenders JWM, Eisenhofer G, Mannelli, et al. Phaeochromocytoma. Lancet 2005;366:665-75. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16112304/","Farrugia FA, Martikos G, Tzanetis G, et al. Pheochromocytoma, diagnosis and treatment: Review of the literature. Endo Regul. 2017;51:168-81. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28858847/","Lenders JW, Duh QY, Eisenhofer G, Gimenez-Roqueplo AP, Grebe SK, Murad MH, et al; Endocrine Society. Pheochromocytoma and paraganglioma: an endocrine society clinical practice guideline. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2014 Jun;99(6):1915-42. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1210/jc.2014-1498"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85869"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"52"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16254"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16254"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2f7f2982-ef48-47a8-b6ff-941d0c8810ad.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2f7f2982-ef48-47a8-b6ff-941d0c8810ad.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":458,"height":381}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85869"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-22T14:39:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-22T14:39:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"52"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103447"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":